title: OTHER CONFERENCES Houston dominates Central Florida - Arkansas Online
text:
AMERICAN ATHLETIC 
NO. 21 HOUSTON 59, CENTRAL FLORIDA 10 
ORLANDO, Fla. -- It took Houston a while to get going Saturday, but once the Cougars got it together late in the first half, they quickly put away winless Central Florida. 
Kenneth Farrow ran for career-high 167 yards and three touchdowns and No. 21 Houston remained undefeated with a 59-10 victory. 
The Cougars (7-0, 4-0 AAC) ran up 600 yards and scored 24 points in a mid-game span of 3 1/2 minutes, winning for the fifth time by 21 points or more. 
Brandon Wilson scored for the Cougars on an 85-yard return of a fumble just 74 seconds into the game. Wilson stripped Cam Stewart of the ball after a third straight UCF completion and ran down the sideline to an easy touchdown, Houston's only score in the first 27 minutes of the game. 
UCF, which entered the game ranked last offensively among 127 teams in the Football Bowl Subdivision, gained 175 yards in the first quarter, 94 of them on a seven-play touchdown drive. When Matthew Wright kicked a 48-yard field to put the Golden Knights up 10-7 with 4:38 left in the first half, they had outgunned Houston by 216 yards to 74. 
But Houston responded with a six-play, 72-yard drive to regain the lead on Farrow's 26-yard touchdown run with 2:27 left in the first half, and the rest of the game was all Cougars. They scored three touchdowns and a field goal over the next 3 1/2 minutes and put the game away with a 28-point third quarter. 
In other games involving AAC teams, Navy quarterback Keenan Reynolds ran for a pair of touchdowns and the Midshipmen forced three consecutive turnovers in the second half for a 31-14 victory over Tulane . ... Quinton Flowers rushed for a South Florida quarterback-record 201 yards and three touchdowns, helping the Bulls beat SMU 38-14 for their first three-game winning streak in four years. ... Gunner Kiel made his first start in a month, threw two touchdown passes and ran for a third as Cincinnati won its first conference game, beating Connecticut 37-13. 
MID-AMERICAN 
NO. 19 TOLEDO 51, MASSACHUSETTS 35 
FOXBOROUGH, Mass. -- Phillip Ely recovered from a poor start and threw four of his five touchdown passes in the second half as No. 19 Toledo stormed back from an 18-point deficit for a victory over Massachusetts. 
Ely was intercepted three times in the first half, but the Rockets (7-0, 4-0 MAC), and are off to their best start since 1997. He completed 26 of 47 passes for 355 yards. 
Terry Swanson ran 21 times for 117 yards and a score for the Rockets, who entered with their highest ranking in Top 25 since climbing to No. 18 in '97. 
Blake Frohnapfel completed 27 of 49 for 240 yards and four TDs for UMass (1-6, 0-3 MAC). The game was played at Gillette Stadium, home of the defending Super Bowl champion New England Patriots. 
In other games involving MAC teams, Matt Johnson passed for five touchdowns for the third consecutive game, and Bowling Green shut out Kent State 48-0. ... Zach Terrell threw for 278 yards and three touchdowns and Western Michigan rolled Miami (Ohio) 35-13. ... Cooper Rush completed 30 of 38 passes for 316 yards and two touchdowns to help Central Michigan beat Ball State 23-21. ... Drew Hare threw four touchdown passes and Joel Bouagnon rushed for 136 yards and a score to help Northern Illinois beat Eastern Michigan 49-21. ... Okezie Alozie returned one of his two interceptions for a touchdown to help lead Buffalo past Ohio 41-17. 
CONFERENCE USA 
Dixon solid for Tech 
RUSTON, La. — Kenneth Dixon (Strong) ran for three touchdowns and caught a pass for another as Louisiana Tech defeated Middle Tennessee 45-16. 
Louisiana Tech (5-3, 3-1 Conference USA) out-rushed Middle Tennessee (3-5, 2-2) with 169 yards to 33. Dixon ran 14 times for 66 yards. 
Jeff Driskel completed 18 of 28 passes for 294 yards with touchdown strikes of 55 yards to Carlos Henderson, and 35 to Dixon. The pass to Henderson broke a 7-7 tie as the Bulldogs took the lead for good. 
In other games involving C-USA teams, a 13-yard pass from Driphus Jackson led Rice on a seven-play, 75-yard game-winning drive in 1:49 to get a 38-31 victory over Army. ... Nick Mullens threw touchdown passes to four different receivers and Mike Thomas topped 100 yards receiving for a school-best fifth consecutive game, leading Southern Mississippi to a 44-10 victory over Charlotte in the first-ever matchup of these teams. … Chase Litton threw for 189 yards and a touchdown to lead Marshall to a 30-13 victory over North Texas. … Alex McGough threw for three touchdowns and ran for another to lead Florida International to a 41-12 victory over Old Dominion. … Mack Leftwich threw a career-high three touchdown passes, including a pair to Tyler Batson, to help Texas-El Paso end a two-game skid and beat Florida Atlantic 27-17. 
MOUNTAIN WEST 
AIR FORCE 42, FRESNO STATE 14 
AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. -- Quarterback Karson Roberts rushed for four touchdowns and caught another on a trick play, helping Air Force overcome a sluggish start to beat Fresno State. 
Roberts' five total touchdowns ties for the second-most in school history, one behind the mark set by QB Dee Dowis in 1989. 
In addition to four short scoring runs, Roberts also hauled in a 20-yard TD pass from receiver Jalen Robinette to help the Falcons (4-3, 3-1 Mountain West) roll to their 10th consecutive home victory. 
Fresno State (2-6, 1-4) jumped out to a 14-0 lead on long runs by Marteze Waller and Dustin Garrison, only to have the Falcons respond with 42 unanswered points. 
Bryan Driskell finished with 144 yards rushing for Air Force and Jacobi Owens added 137, along with a score. Even without injured fullbacks Shayne Davern and D.J. Johnson, the Falcons still rushed for 458 yards. 
In other games involving Mountain West teams, James Butler rushed for 134 yards with two touchdowns and Nevada came back to beat Hawaii 30-20. The Wolf Pack scored 17 points in the fourth quarter, including Brent Zuzo’s tiebreaking 30-yard field goal and Butler’s 1-yard plunge with 2:20 left, which followed Nevada’s third interception of the day. … Tyler Ervin rushed for 263 yards and San Jose State beat New Mexico 31-21. 
Sports on 10/25/2015
